

trace packets 
	mtr
	tcpdump

detect hosts on network
	fping
	nmap -sP 192.168.0.* | grep Host

Reports on listening daemons
	netstat
		reports
			ant		show programs bound to ports for TCP address family
			i		interfaces
			r		kernel routing tables
			M		masqueraded connections
		options
			p		show name of program
			c		continuous display
			t		tcp
			l		listening servers (*)
			a		show all
						with -i, show interfaces that are not up
						with n, show both listening & established connections
		Examples
			show all running sessions and daemons
				netstat -untap  
				netstat --tcp --udp --listening --program --numeric
			shows running daemons
				netstat -ltp

darkstat
	Easy monitoring of bandwidth
	included webserver with graphs of bandwidth, usage by site 

capturing network traffic
	tcpdump 
		raw info
		good article
			http://www.informit.com/articles/article.asp?p=352988&seqNum=3
		
		e.g.
			Test ping through firewall using tcpdump
			https://lists.linux-foundation.org/pipermail/bridge/2005-October/004724.html
			tcpdump -i eth2 icmp


	ethereal (graphical) / tethereal (cmd line)
		friendlier interface

	tshark/wireshark
		-D	list interfaces
		-i	interface name or # from -D


Wake-on-lan
	http://www.debian-administration.org/articles/122
	
	install on client: ethtool
	Enable interface:
		in /etc/networking/interfaces:
			ifac inet eth0 dhcp
				 up ethtool -s $IFACE wol g

	install on host issuing command: wakeonlan
	get client hw address:
		/usr/sbin/arp <hostname>
	wakeonlan <client mac address>

